countries <- c("United States of America", "India", "China", "Mexico", "Canada")
selected_countries <- gap %>% 
  filter(name %in% countries) %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=time, y=co2, col=name)) +
  geom_line()
print(selected_countries)
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

#### We can say that China is much higher in total CO2 emissions compared to the others, with US in second. This was not always the case, however China skyrocketed in terms of total CO2 emissions in the 2000s, when they passed America.

gap_1960 <- gap %>% 
  filter(time == "1960")
p <- ggplot(gap_1960, aes(GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, alpha = 0.5, col=region, size=totalPopulation)) +
  geom_point()
print(p)
## Warning: Removed 128 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

#### It seems as though there is a positive correlation between GDP per capita and life expectancy. Life expectancy increases at a high rate with an increase in GDP per capita however eventually it slows down significantly. This implies theres a limit on how high life expectancy can increase

5.

gap %>% 
  filter(time %in% c(1960, 2019)) %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  summarize(avg_le_1960 = mean(lifeExpectancy[time == 1960], na.rm = TRUE), avg_le_2019 = mean(lifeExpectancy[time == 2019], na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(leGrowth = ((avg_le_2019 - avg_le_1960)-1)/100) %>% 
  arrange(desc(leGrowth))
